**Q1: Give a short summary of the story (5 points)**  
The story recounts how **Ximen Bao**, a governor of Ye during the reign of King Wen of Wei, investigates the local custom of sacrificing a girl to the river god, **Hebo**, which is a fraudulent practice used by local officials and witches to extort money from the people. By pretending to support the ritual, Ximen Bao publicly exposes the fraud by throwing the chief witch and officials into the river. He then leads the people to build irrigation channels, improving agriculture and prosperity in the region.

---

**Q2: What kind of women were usually the victims in the story (2 points)**  
The victims were usually **young, attractive girls from poor families**, selected by the witch to be sacrificed to the river god.

---

**Q3: Who were deemed to benefit from the old practice of offering girls? (2 points)**  
The **three elders (三老), magistrates (廷掾), and witches (祝巫)** benefited from the practice, as they collected money from the people and shared the profits among themselves.

---

**Q4: Did the protagonist use wits or force to deal with the situation? Explain (5 points)**  
Ximen Bao used **wits** to deal with the situation. He pretended to support the ritual to gain the trust of the officials and the public. When the time came, he used the excuse that the girl was not beautiful enough to demand the witch and officials to go and report to the river god, thereby **throwing them into the river**. This clever strategy allowed him to **expose the fraud and eliminate the corrupt officials without direct confrontation**, minimizing resistance and public unrest.

